So `getVerse` should return an array of two strings, or `recite` should split the verse string by `\n` and 
flatten the result.
Let's modify `getVerse` to return an array of two strings, and update `recite` to handle it, or just change 
`getVerse` to return an array and flatten in `recite`.

Actually, it's easier to just make `getVerse` return an array of two lines, and then in `recite`, we can use 
`flatMap` or just push and spread.

Let's change `getVerse` to return an array:
```javascript
const getVerse = (n) => {
  if (n === 0) {
    return [
      'No more bottles of beer on the wall, no more bottles of beer.',
      'Go to the store and buy some more, 99 bottles of beer on the wall.'
    ];
  }
  if (n === 1) {
    return [
      '1 bottle of beer on the wall, 1 bottle of beer.',
      'Take it down and pass it around, no more bottles of beer on the wall.'
    ];
  }
  if (n === 2) {
    return [
      '2 bottles of beer on the wall, 2 bottles of beer.',
      'Take one down and pass it around, 1 bottle of beer on the wall.'
    ];
  }
  return [
    `${n} bottles of beer on the wall, ${n} bottles of beer.`,
    `Take one down and pass it around, ${n - 1} bottles of beer on the wall.`
  ];
};
```

And `recite`:
```javascript
export const recite = (initialBottlesCount, takeDownCount) => {
  const verses = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < takeDownCount; i++) {
    verses.push(...getVerse(initialBottlesCount - i));
    if (i < takeDownCount - 1) {
      verses.push('');
    }
  }
  return verses;
};
```

